layout: layouts/base.njk
title: "Mobile Notary Denver, CO | Same-Day Traveling Notary — Denver Mobile Notary Service"
description: "A commissioned Colorado notary comes to you — home, office, hospital, or coffee shop — anywhere in metro Denver, often same-day. Upfront pricing, payment before the appointment. Call or book online."
permalink: "/"
faqs:
  - q: "How much does a mobile notary cost in Denver?"
    a: "Colorado caps the notarial act itself at $15 per document in person and $25 for remote online notarization. The travel fee is separate and is what varies — most Denver-metro mobile visits total roughly $45–$95 depending on distance, time of day, and number of documents. We quote the full price before booking and process payment before the appointment, so there are no surprises at the table."
  - q: "Can a notary come to me the same day in Denver?"
    a: "Usually, yes. We dispatch commissioned notaries across the Denver metro seven days a week, 7 AM to 9 PM, and most requests placed before mid-afternoon can be served the same day. Hospital and care-facility visits are prioritized."
  - q: "What ID do I need for a notarization in Colorado?"
    a: "A current, unexpired government-issued photo ID — a driver's license, state ID card, passport, or military ID all work. If the signer has no valid ID, Colorado allows identification by a credible witness who knows the signer and has their own valid ID. Tell us in advance and we'll walk you through it."
  - q: "Should I sign my document before the notary arrives?"
    a: "No. For most notarial acts the signature must be made in the notary's presence. If a document arrives pre-signed, the notary may have to have you re-sign or may be unable to complete the notarization. Bring the document complete but unsigned."
  - q: "Is remote online notarization legal in Colorado?"
    a: "Yes. Colorado has authorized remote online notarization (RON), performed over secure audio-video with identity verification. It's legal for most documents and the state caps the RON notarial fee at $25 per act. Some documents and some receiving parties still require in-person notarization — we'll confirm which route fits your document before booking."
---
